Spatial Visualization with R AKA maps

  • The maps in R displays maps - projection code and larger maps are in other packages (mapproj and mapdata)

  • ggmap enables visualisations by combining the layed grammar of graphics implementation of ggplot2 with spatial information of static maps from:

    • Google Maps
    • OpenStreetMap
    • Stamen Maps, or
    • CloudMade Maps

  • Since ggplot2 is an implementation of the layered grammar of graphics. the coordinate system is fixed to the Mercator projection"

  • mapproj adds more projections

Defining locations

Locations can be defined by:

  1. Location or address
  2. Logitude and Latitude
  3. Defining an area bound by 4 points:
    • Lower left long
    • Lower left lat
    • upper right long
    • upper right lat
#Method 1: Address/ location
my_location1<- "Melbourne"
my_location1
[1] "Melbourne"
#Method 2: long/lat
my_location2<- c(lon=-95.3632715, lat=29.7632836)
my_location2
      lon       lat 
-95.36327  29.76328 
#Method 3: bound area
myLocation3 <- c(-130, #lower left long
                 30, #lower left lat
                 -105, #upper right long
                 50) #upper right lat
myLocation3
[1] -130   30 -105   50

An important geo-feature for geo-rekated applications is getting latitude and lonitude for a given address.

  • Previously could be done using geocode in ggmap with a Google Map API but now you need your own personal API key.
  • .: Much easier to use tmaptools

Drawing a map of a defined location

Now we can map based on location. There are four (4) map sources with multiple map types:

  1. stamen:
    • e.g.“terrain”, “toner”, “watercolour”, etc…
  2. Google
    • API key required
    • “roadmap”, “terrain”, “satellite”, “hybrid”
  3. osm:
    • open street map
  4. cloudmade:
    • API key required
    • 1000s maps available

You can get the maps by trying get_mapname (e.g.: get_googlemap) Type in ?get_mapname to see what map types are availble!

#define the location
my_location4 <- geocode_OSM("Melbourne")
#get the box vector from the results
bbox_vector <- as.vector(my_location4$bbox)
#get the bits of the vector to create the box!
bbox1 <- c(
  left = bbox_vector[1],
  bottom = bbox_vector[2],
  right   = bbox_vector[3],
  top  = bbox_vector[4])
#draw the map
#get the stamenmap maps
my_map <- get_stamenmap(
  
  #tell it what to map
  bbox = bbox1,
  
  #choose a map type
  maptype = "watercolor",
  
  #level of zoom
  zoom = 13
  
)

Projecting a map

Mercator projections are:

  • equally apaced straight meridians
  • conformal
  • straight compass courses

Albers projections are:

  • equal area
  • conic
  • uses two standard parallels

go to ?map to find all the projection types.

Projections and Gridlines

require(mapproj)
Loading required package: mapproj
package <U+393C><U+3E31>mapproj<U+393C><U+3E32> was built under R version 3.5.3
#get map dta
#lat &amp, amp; lon for boundaries
m<- map("usa", plot = FALSE)
#try the mercator projection
map(m, projection = "mercator")
#draw grid lines
map.grid(m)

#try the albers projection
#
map(m, projection = "albers",
    par = c(39, 45))
#draw grid lines
map.grid(m)

#map the whole world
m <- map("world", plot = FALSE)
map(m, #what to map
    
    #projection type
    proj = "azequalarea",
    
    #choose where the "centre" is
    #An optional vector c(latitude,longitude,rotation) which describes where the "North Pole" should be when computing the projection. 
    #Normally this is c(90,0), which is appropriate for cylindrical and conic projections.
    orient = c(41, -74, 0))
map.grid(m, 
         
         #grid colour
         col = 6)

Points on the graph

map(m, #what to map
    
    #projection type
    proj = "orth",
    
    #choose where the "centre" is
    orient = c(41, -74, 0))
projection failed for some data
#add grid lines
map.grid(
  m,
  col = 4,
  
  #number of equally spaced longitude and latitude lines
  nx = 5,
  ny = 6,
  
  label = FALSE,
  
  lty = 2
)
#add some points
points(
  
  #tell is where to put the point
  #mapproject converts lonitude and latitude into projected coordinates
  mapproject(
    list(y = 41, #long
         x = -74)), #lat
    
    #colour of point
    col = 3,
    
    #what kind of mark
    pch = "x",
    
  #size of x
    cex = 2
    
)

Using Quick Plot

qmplot is the ggmap equivalent to the ggplot2 function qplot and allows for the quick plotting of maps with data/models/etc.

Build a map using the crime dataset:

  • Lightly cleaned Houston crime from January 2010 to August 2010 geocoded with Google Maps
help(crime)
head(crime)

Plot the murders on a map

#get the subset of data where the offence is murder
murder <- subset(crime, 
              offense == "murder")
qmplot(
  #lonitude values
  x = lon, 
  
  #latitude values
  y = lat,
  
  #data
  data = murder,
  
  #colour
  colour = I("red"),
  
  #size of data points
  size = I(3),
  
  #vector of the form c(number, color), where number is in [0, 1] and color is a character string indicating the color of the darken. 0 indicates no darkening, 1 indicates a black-out.
  #how dark the map is (??)
  darken = 0.3
)

Chloropleth Maps

Plot a chloropleth map of unemployment rates in the US.

help(unemp)
head(unemp)
help("county.fips")
head(county.fips)
#what data to use 
data("unemp")
#define the intervals for the chloromap
Intervals <- as.numeric(
  
  #Cut uses the base function cut to classify the values of a Raster* object according to which interval they fall in.
  cut(
    #which column needs to be turned into class/ categoies
    unemp$unemp,
    
    #set the categories
    #in this case it will be ("<2%","2-4%","4-6%","6-8%","8-10%",">10%")
    #first number in inclusive, second number is not
    c(0,2,4,6,8,10,100)
  )
)
#match unemployment data to map regions using the fips codes
data("county.fips")
Matches <- Intervals[
  
  #will match the first one to the second one
  match(
    #which column to look up
    county.fips$fips,
    
    unemp$fips
  )
]
#DRAW THE MAP
#choose the colours for each interval
colors <- c("#ffffd4","#fee391","#fec44f","#fe9929","#d95f0e","#993404")
map("county", #what to map: county data
    
    #match level to colour
    col = colors[Matches], 
    
    #colour in the map
    fill = TRUE,
    
    resolution = 0,
    
    #line type around county areas
    lty = 0,
    
    #type of projection
    projection = "polyconic"
    
  
)
#add state boundries layer
map("state",
    
    #colour
    col = "black",
    
    #dont colour in
    fill = FALSE,
    
    #add to previous map
    add = TRUE,
    
    #type of line
    lty = 1,
    
    #line thikness
    lwd = 0.3,
    
    projection = "polyconic")
#add a title
title("Unemployment by county 2009")
#add a legend
Legend <- c("<2%", "2-4%","4-6%","6-8%","8-10%",">10%")
legend("bottomright",
       Legend,
       horiz = TRUE,
       fill = colors)

Flow Map

library(geosphere)
map("state")
lat_ca <- 39.164141
lon_ca <- -121.640625
 
lat_me <- 45.213004
lon_me <- -68.906250
inter <- gcIntermediate( #Get intermediate points (way points) between the two locations with longitude/latitude coordinates. gcIntermediate is based on a spherical model of the earth and internally uses distCosine.
  
  #point 1
  c(lon_ca, lat_ca),
  
  #point 2
  c(lon_me, lat_me),
  
  #number of intermediate points
  n = 50,
  
  #add p1 and p2 to the result?
  addStartEnd = TRUE
)
#add the line on top of the map
lines(inter)

Example: plotting american airline (AA) flights

#load csv data from website
airports <- read.csv("http://datasets.flowingdata.com/tuts/maparcs/airports.csv", header = TRUE)
flights <- read.csv("http://datasets.flowingdata.com/tuts/maparcs/flights.csv", header = TRUE, as.is = TRUE)
 
head(airports)
head(flights)
# create a world map and limited it to around US areas.
xlim <- c(-171.738281, -56.601563)
ylim <- c(12.039321, 71.856229)
#draw the map
map(
  "world",
  
  #map colour
  col = "#f2f2f2",
  
  fill = TRUE,
  
  #background colour
  bg  = "white",
  
  #link width
  lwd = 0.05,
  
  xlim = xlim,
  ylim = ylim
  
)
#plot the flights
#get AA flights only
flights_AA <- flights[flights$airline == "AA",]
#for each row in the flights database we need to add a line to the graph
for (j in 1:length(flights_AA$airline)){
  
  
  #airport 1 (point 1)
  #get the airport from the first row of the flights and return the long and lat where the iata (abbrev) matches it from the aiport database
  air1 <- airports[airports$iata == flights_AA[j,]$airport1,]
  
  #same for airport 2
  air2 <- airports[airports$iata == flights_AA[j,]$airport2,]
  
  inter <- gcIntermediate(
    
    #point 1
    c(air1[1,]$long,
      air1[1,]$lat),
    
    #point 2
    c(air2[1,]$long,
      air2[1,]$lat),
    
    n = 100,
    
    addStartEnd = TRUE
  )
  
  #add the lines
  lines(inter, 
        col = "black",
        lwd = 0.8)
    
}
